===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|ojp|ja}} root verb {{m|ja|す|tr=su||to do}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref>

As with all verbs, during the Middle Japanese stage in the [[w:Kamakura period|Kamakura]] and [[w:Muromachi period|Muromachi]] periods, the {{m|ja|終止形|tr=shūshikei||terminal or sentence-ending form}} was gradually lost as the {{m|ja|連体形|tr=rentaikei||attributive form}} came to be used for both the attributive and terminal grammatical roles, realigning the conjugations.

====Pronunciation====
{{ja-pron|する|acc=h|y=kun|acc_ref=NHK}}

====Alternative forms====
* {{ja-l|為る}} {{qualifier|rare}}

====Verb====
{{ja-verb|type=3|tr=trans}}

# to [[do]]
#: {{ja-usex|何を'''して'''いますか。|なに を '''して''' います か。|What are you '''doing'''?}}
# to wear (accessories)
#: {{ja-usex|ネクタイを'''する'''。|ネクタイ を '''する'''。|I '''wear''' a necktie.}}

=====Usage notes=====
The verb {{lang|ja|する}} (“to do”) is seldom written in kanji ({{ja-l|為る}}).

It is common to use {{lang|ja|する}} after certain nouns to indicate that the noun is being done; this is ''highly'' [[productive]], meaning many nouns can be used as verbs in this way. Some examples are:
* {{m|ja|勉強|tr=benkyō||studying}} → {{lang|ja|勉強'''する'''}} (''benkyō '''suru''''', “to do studying” → “to study”)
* {{m|ja|旅行|tr=ryokō||journey}} → {{lang|ja|旅行'''する'''}} (''ryokō '''suru''''', “to do journey” → “to travel”)

=====Synonyms=====
* {{sense|to do}} {{ja-l|成す}}, {{ja-l|為す|なす|nasu}} {{qualifier|somewhat archaic, usage is more limited}}
* {{sense|to do}} {{ja-l|行う|おこなう|okonau}} {{gloss|to carry out}}
* {{sense|used to make a verb}} {{m|ja|る|〜る|tr=-ru}}, a much less productive suffix for turning a noun into a verb

